<DOC><DOCNO> AP890810-0029 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0359EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     08-10 0524</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,520</SECOND><HEAD>Panel Focuses on Health Care Financing</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Social Security advisory panel has targetedthe financing of a health care system as its first mission.   Deborah Steelman, head of the Advisory Council on SocialSecurity, said the current health care system ``overlaps,duplicates, omits, confuses'' and leaves many needy people withoutadequate care. She said the panel must ``develop recommendationsfor a sound, sustainable health care financing system'' to face newstrains with the aging of the Baby Boom generation.   Ms. Steelman said the current Medicare system ``is projected tobe insolvent by early in the next century, before the Baby Boom haseven begun to enter retirement.''   The 13-member advisory council holds its opening meeting onThursday and Friday. Such a panel is appointed every four years toexamine issues affecting the Social Security, Medicare and Medicaidprograms.   Ms. Steelman said the council hopes to issue a draft report onhealth care financing by July 1990 and recommendations on thefinancing and role of Social Security benefits by December 1990. Afinal report to Congress and the Department of Health and HumanServices is due in January 1991.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>US Dependents Authorized To Return To China</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Although the State Department is recommendingthat Americans defer non-essential travel to China, improvedsecurity conditions will enable about 260 dependents of U.S.government employees in China who were evacuated in June to return.   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said that although thesecurity situation has improved, it is still more unsettled thanbefore the imposition of marital law in May.   The dependents were ordered home three days after Chinesemilitary forces routed demonstrators who had occupied TienanmenSquare in Beijing for weeks.   As part of the disturbances, Chinese troops fired their weaponsin the vicinity of a compound where diplomats and other foreignresidents live. The U.S. Embassy's chief of security said bulletsflew through a window into a room where his two children werewatching television.   The incident prompted a strong protest by the U.S. Embassy toChinese authorities. Ms. Tutwiler was unable to say whether theissue was resolved to the satisfaction of U.S. officials.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>Judge Gives Commerce Until Friday To Answer New Petition</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Commerce Department has until Friday toanswer claims by the National Wildlife Federation that thegovernment is not protecting endangered sea turtles from extinction.   The federation contends that the government's own studies showrestricted shrimp-fishing tow times are ineffective.   An order Wednesday by a U.S. District Court judge also asksCommerce to respond to the federation's request that the agencyenforce a law that requires shrimper to equip their nets withdevices that let sea turtles escape.   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, under an order by federalJudge Thomas Hogan to protect sea turtles, this week requiredshrimpers to either use the turtle excluder devices, which theyloathe, or limit trawl times to 105 minutes.   The same day those rules took effect, the wildlife federationfiled its petition with the court seeking access to governmentdocuments that it claims indicate tow times jeopardize theendangered sea turtle.</TEXT></DOC>